erfluidity.com/banner5.jpg" border="1"></A></center></html></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ukomikino.showPublicProfile?language=EN>komikino</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/4/02 3:26:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1531.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://schleiferstudios.com/small2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Are details always good?</span><hr size=1> I was talking with Ben Dunn many years ago and he told me that it is always good to have at least <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> ONE</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> detailed picture per page. The rest of the panels can have moderate detail. All depends of course on what you are doing. <br>If you are drawing a real life object (let's say a Subaru WRX), make sure you have lots of reference pics to draw it as close to realistic as you can. I'm sure you've seen many comics where they have modern cars, jets, etc and you look at them and say &quot;What the hell is he trying to draw?&quot; For some of the best detailed vehicles, weapons, etc, look for the Twilight X collected book coming out in a few months from Antarctic Press. Joe Wight draws some amazingly detailed things. Makes me want to cry, it looks soooo good. <p>Komikino/Richman<br>"You sank my Scrabbleship!"<BR><a href=http://www.schleiferstudios.com>www.schleiferstudios.com</a></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showNextMessage?topicID=1531.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1531.topic&index=4><img src=http://www.polykarbon